As shown in Fig. 4
                        A, F420/F575 gradually increases with increasing glucose concentration. The relationship between F420/F575 and glucose concentration shows good linearity in the 1–15 μM range with the regression equation determined to be: F420/F575 = 0.032[glucose] (μM) + 0.416 (r = 0.999). The LOD was calculated to be 0.18 μM using the equation LOD = 3S/K, where S represents the standard deviation of the blank signal (0.00196) and K is the slope of the working curve (0.032). The proposed method is comparable or superior to those of most previously reported glucose fluorescence probes (Table 1
                        ). Moreover, our constructed ratiometric sensing method can eliminate false signals originating from the influence of the surrounding environment and remove the fluctuations in probe concentration and instrument stability, providing more reliable measurements.

The ability of the GQD/AuNC/Fe2+ nanosystem to detect glucose in human blood samples was next evaluated. Sera were diluted 100 times and incubated with GOx at 35 °C for 10 min, and then mixed with GQDs/AuNCs/Fe2+ for 5 min. The concentration of glucose was calculated from the F420/F575 value and the calibration curve provided in Fig. 4A. Fig. 5
                         reveals that the developed method provides results that are consistent with those obtained using the conventional GOx-HRP-TMB colorimetric method; the correlation equation for both sets of data was determined to be: Y = 0.994X – 0.03 (r = 0.998). The feasibility of our probe was further validated by standard addition experiments. The recovery of glucose from four serum sample ranged from 101.9∼109.6 % with RSDs of 0.9∼3.0 % (Table 2
                        ). This outcome demonstrates that the developed method is very accurate and reliable, and can be used for blood and other biological samples.
